@NODE N0 "Introduction"

  Hi, and welcome.  ARead is a program I have made to satisfy my
need  for  a small and fast text reader.  I only have a 68000 in
my aged A2000 and it seems to take MultiView forever to load and
display  very  small  textfiles like fileid.diz's and .readme's.
So I sat down and started to create ARead V1.0.

  Since  V1.0  some @{"changes" LINK N7} have taken place that has made ARead
even  more powerful and IMHO much much better.  Many thanks must
go  to  the several people whom have EMailed me and motivated me
to  make  these changes, especially Nils Goers who had some very
good suggestions, all of which are now implemented in ARead.

Please take the time to try ARead, I'm sure you will like it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE N1 "Features"

 - ARead  is  Small  and  Fast.   It's programmed in  100% 680x0
   Assembly language to attain these goals.

 - ARead is PURE and can be made resident.

 - ARead will load any file but will NOT display more than 9999
   lines.

 - ARead will NOT wordwrap any lines in the textfile.

 - ARead  does  not like lines of text that are longer than  254
   characters. Strange behaviour may occur :^)

 - ARead does not like multi coloured text (ANSI).

 - ARead ONLY displays text in one colour.

 - ARead  will change TAB and CR (peecee style) characters  into
   spaces. ARead will NOT pad TABS.

 - From WB or CLI you need supply no  filename if you want ARead
   to open a FileRequester so you can select the file to ARead.

 - I'm sure there is something I forgot to mention :^)


@ENDNODE

@NODE N3 "ToolTypes"

Using  ARead  from  Workbench is pretty easy.  Select a textfile
icon  on  the  workbench  and  from  the  Workbench menus select
Icons>Information.   Change  the  icon's  default tool to ARead.
That's  all you have to do, all the tooltypes (below) are purely
optional.   Here is a listing of the tooltypes and what they do.
If  you  don't  know about setting tooltypes I would suggest you
have a read of your Amiga's manuals.

PUBSCREEN
Name  of the public screen that you would like ARead to open on.
If  the  screen  is  not  open  then  ARead will fallback to the
default public screen (usually Workbench). NOTE: PUBSCREEN NAMES
ARE CASE DEPENDANT!!

FONTNAME
Name  of  the  font  that  you want ARead to use when displaying
text.   Default=font of screen ARead opened on.  NOTE:  IF NAMED
FONT  CANNOT  BE  OPENED THEN SCREEN FONT WILL BE USED.  IF THIS
CANNOT BE OPENED THEN THE DEFAULT SYSTEM FONT WILL BE USED.

FONTSIZE
Height of the font you specified. Default=8.

LEFT
X-Position of ARead window. Default=0

TOP
Y-Position of ARead window. Default=16

WIDTH
Width of ARead window. Default=640

HEIGHT
Height of ARead window. Default=240


Pretty  easy  eh?   Oh,  if  you want you can set tooltypes (the
above  ones)  in  the Aread executable too.  This will mean that
these  options  will be used when the Aread executable is double
clicked.   Tooltypes  for  individual files override the ones in
ARead's executable.
@ENDNODE

@NODE N4 "CLI Args"

When  calling  ARead  form  the CLI the arguments you pass to it
have  the  same  names and functions as the Workbench tooltypes.

N=NAME/A
Name  of  the  file you want to ARead.  If no name is specified,
ARead will open an ASL file requester so you can choose one.

P=PUBSCREEN/S
Name  of the public screen that you would like ARead to open on.
If  the  screen  is  not  open  then  ARead will fallback to the
default public screen (usually Workbench). NOTE: PUBSCREEN NAMES
ARE CASE DEPENDANT!!

F=FONTNAME/S
Name  of  the  font  that  you want ARead to use when displaying
text.   Default=font of screen ARead opened on.  NOTE:  IF NAMED
FONT  CANNOT  BE  OPENED THEN SCREEN FONT WILL BE USED.  IF THIS
CANNOT BE OPENED THEN THE DEFAULT SYSTEM FONT WILL BE USED.

F=FONTSIZE/N
Height of the font you specified. Default=8.

L=LEFT/N
X-Position of ARead window. Default=0

T=TOP/N
Y-Position of ARead window. Default=16

W=WIDTH/N
Width of ARead window. Default=640

H=HEIGHT/N
Height of ARead window. Default=240


Here is an example...

ARead docs:aread.doc FONTNAME=xen.font FONTSIZE=11

This will read the file "docs:aread.doc" and use the xen 11 font
when displaying it.

ARead docs:aread.doc F=xen.font S=11

The above example will do exactly the same thing but is a little
faster to type :^)

If  the  ARead  executable  has it's H and P protection bits set
then  ARead will become resident automatically after it has been
run  once.   After the first time you run ARead it will not have
to  load  form  disk  again.   To  enable  this feature type the
following commandline at CLI/Shell...

protect C:ARead HP ADD

@ENDNODE

@NODE N5 "Hotkeys"

  Whilst AReading a text file you can use the following key/s to
perform several useful functions.

 KEY/S                 FUNCTION

 ESCAPE .............. quit

 CURSORUP ............ previous line
 CURSORDOWN .......... next line

 SPACE ............... next page
 SHIFT+SPACE ......... previous page

 SHIFT+CURSORDOWN .... next page
 SHIFT+CURSORUP ...... previous page

 CONTROL+CURSORDOWN .. last page
 CONTROL+CURSORUP .... first page
@ENDNODE

